"{\"content\":{\"body\":\"```\\nHigh-level modules should not rely on low-level modules, and both high-level and low-level modules should rely on abstraction.\\nAbstraction should not depend on concreteness, concreteness should depend on abstraction.\\nWhen implementing the dependency inversion principle, we need to program for the abstract layer, and inject the objects of the concrete class into other objects through Dependency Injection (DI). Dependency injection refers to when an object has a dependency relationship with other objects. At the same time, the dependent objects are injected through abstraction. There are three commonly used injection methods, namely: construction injection, set value injection (Setter injection) and interface injection. Spring's IOC is a model of this implementation.\\n\\nViewing the essence of the dependency inversion principle from a Java perspective is: interface-oriented (abstract) programming.\\n\\nEach concrete class should have its interface or base class, or both.\\nThe reference object in the class should be an interface or base class.\\nAny concrete class should not derive subclasses.\\nTry not to override the methods in the base class.\\nUse in combination with the Richter substitution principle.\\n```\",\"timestamp\":1637331923,\"title\":\"\\nPrecautions for relying on the reversal principle\"},\"digest\":\"OUXUwWdWW-HUqmyKDne9y1wTLoC8HUE0eI71WrY83lM\",\"authorship\":{\"contributor\":\"0x8fC645e6a176F07395B8f44196d1443772FE9d57\",\"signingKey\":\"{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"NIYH-7XF8Am0JA6bSL7qG7RDhtSeGTO5paA4zw2r6IM\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"XqIW2Gcvpg9RZrZO23-_hTsnykNTY7fmDAjFgBjt7TU\\\"}\",\"signature\":\"k14sRMnGwYLyALobOcO-DdRNXYDxAw9X-EY_i_WmbyNU46cuvWW8SRAfbu5lshx2xGEt8AAKWbrcYCJo_OpjdQ\",\"signingKeySignature\":\"0x321ba45dcef9f44037d1ab522f16955d07befdaca8b9ad41a6dd7d424715d97b081b5e7c678e1b4e4f545c0e955905832cc515bb147613410f9b62eb771